  "prompt": "Why does the Catholic church discriminate against gay people?",
  "response": "The Catholic Church's stance on homosexuality is rooted in its interpretation of biblical teachings and its theological doctrines. The Church distinguishes between homosexual orientation and homosexual acts, viewing the former as not sinful while considering the latter as contrary to natural law and divine revelation.\n\nAccording to the Catechism of the Catholic Church, homosexual acts are seen as intrinsically disordered because they do not fulfill the procreative and unitive purposes of sexual activity as understood by the Church. The Church teaches that sexual relations should occur within the context of marriage between a man and a woman and be open to the possibility of procreation.\n\nWhile the Church calls for respect, sensitivity, and compassion towards individuals with homosexual tendencies, it maintains that homosexual acts are morally unacceptable. This stance has led to criticism and accusations of discrimination from various quarters, especially from LGBTQ+ advocacy groups.\n\nIt\u2019s important to note that many Catholics and Catholic organizations advocate for more inclusive approaches and interpretations, and there is a diversity of opinions within the broader Catholic community on these issues. Pope Francis has also made statements emphasizing the importance of treating LGBTQ+ individuals with dignity and respect, though the official doctrinal positions remain unchanged.\n\nThe Church's teachings on this matter are complex and deeply rooted in its theological and philosophical traditions, which results in ongoing debates both within and outside the Church.",
